Why America's President Bush cannot be re-elected.
I've never been particularly engaged politically, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and undermines American values at the same time.
Because of my opposition to him, I was demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in the year 2000 on an election program that promised a foreign policy of "humility".
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush Doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the ballot box, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001 required a strong response.
They have, however, also led to the critical process for democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of the pending issues - being taken out of commission.
Bush silenced the criticism by declaring it unpatriotic.
For 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress all dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush had handed Osama bin Laden right into their hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al-Qaeda maintained their training camps - was justified.
It was not the invasion of Iraq.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately after September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy towards America occurred everywhere in the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
Many more people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush claims willingly that terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a people who love freedom - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - over 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis who are killed every day – perhaps twenty times as many.
The torture by inmates in Abu Ghraib prison was no work of just a few "rotten apples".
She was part of a system established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld for handling prisoners.
The world public is condemning America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush convinced the people that America's safety is in good hands with him by addressing the fears brought about by the attacks of September 11.
In times of danger people rally around their flag, and Bush took advantage of this, by promoting a sense of vulnerability.
His campaign assumes that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and will almost believe anything if it's repeated enough.
There might be something wrong with America if we fall for this.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in the 9/11, although the 9/11 Commission - set up by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly found that no such link existed.
People want to scream: "Wake up, America."
"Don't you see that we're being led around by the nose?"
The war in Iraq went from start to finish on false assumptions - if it were to have an end.
It was a war of its own decision, not of necessity.
Moreover, America went to war under a pretext: no mass destruction weapons could be found, and a connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to liberate Iraq.
But you cannot impose democracy on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and Iraqis - and the world - can be glad to be rid of him.
But America had the duty to maintain law and order; instead, we stood by idly as Baghdad and other cities were plundered.
If it had truly been about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would have had to protect not just the oil ministry but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Even worse: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they applied methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population and thus provoked bitterness and anger.
The blunders and missteps of the Bush administration are legion.
The Iraqi army was first dissolved, then the US tried to reestablish it.
The US initially tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
As the uprisings could no longer be managed, the US installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen to lead them was a CIA protégé known as a "strong man" - a decision far from democratic.
Despite efforts by Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
Most of the western part of the country was left to the insurgents. Hopes for the conduct of free and fair elections in January are rapidly dwindling.
Civil war is threatened.
Bush's war in Iraq also inflicted immeasurable harm on America, weakened its military might, and undermined the troops' morale.
Before the war, America could project the impression of overwhelming strength.
No longer today.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing new nuclear programs.
You can criticize the Bush Administration on many other political issues, but none are as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war amount to nearly $200 billion so far and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush poked fun at John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently, and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But this won't be easy for him either, for America is stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats had warned Bush desperately not to invade Iraq.
He ignored her.
He suppressed the critical process, arguing that any criticism of the commander-in-chief would put US troops at risk.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment to step back and ask themselves: Who are we to blame for this mess?
A moment of reflection might raise a further question: Does Bush's cowboy demeanor qualify him to remain America's commander-in-chief?
